    <convention>
    <title>Constant functions</title>
    <p>
        Given a function <m>f</m> defined on a set <m>D</m>, we say that <m>f</m> is on constant on <m>D</m> if there is a complex number <m>w_0\in \C</m> such that <m>f(z)=w_0</m> for all <m>z\in D</m>. We will write <m>f\vert_D=w_0</m> in this case. 
    </p>
</convention>
<definition xml:id="d_locally_constant">
<title>Locally constant</title>
<statement>
<p>
A function <m>f</m> is locally constant on a set <m>D</m> if for all <m>z_0\in U</m> there is an open ball <m>B_r(z_0)\subseteq U</m> such that <m>f</m> is constant on <m>B_r(z_0)\cap D</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>


<theorem xml:id="th_zero_deriv">
<title>Functions of derivative zero</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>f</m> be defined on the open set <m>U</m>. The following statements are equivalent. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>f</m> is locally constant on <m>U</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>f'(z)=0</m> for all <m>z\in U</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
As a consequence, if we assume further that <m>U</m> is connected, then <m>f'\vert_U=0</m> if and only if <m>f</m> is a constant function. 
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
